minutely concerning my father, and here I named my cousin."She most of all," said Ernest, "requires consolation; she accusedherself of having caused the death of my brother, and that made hervery wretched.  But since the murderer has been discovered--""The murderer discovered!  Good God! how can that be? who could attemptto pursue him?  It is impossible; one might as well try to overtake thewinds, or confine a mountain-stream with a straw.  I saw him too; hewas free last night!""I do not know what you mean," replied my brother, in accents ofwonder, "but to us the discovery we have made completes our misery.  Noone would believe it at first; and even now Elizabeth will not beconvinced, notwithstanding all the evidence.  Indeed, who would creditthat Justine Moritz, who was so amiable, and fond of all the family,could suddenly become so capable of so frightful, so appalling a crime?""Justine Moritz!  Poor, poor girl, is she the accused?  But it iswrongfully; every one knows that; no one believes it, surely, Ernest?""No one did at first; but several circumstances came out, that havealmost forced conviction upon us; and her own behaviour has been soconfused, as to add to the evidence of facts a weight that, I fear,leaves no hope for doubt.  But she will be tried today, and you willthen hear all."He then related that, the morning on which the murder of poor Williamhad been discovered, Justine had been taken ill, and confined to herbed for several days.  During this interval, one of the servants,